Puzzle solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin found out this with the help of experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday night. Progress had also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so vigorously against tickling, only to then demand more.
After all, it has also been shown why the mere approach of a tickling hand triggers laughter even before the touch, which is due to a deep-seated layer in the cerebrum, which already triggers laughter during the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, earlier research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans. "Laughter" is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touch
Until now, it had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-contact and contact by others – which is why people cannot tickle themselves. However, in the experiments on rats, the Berlin-based researchers found that the laughter and the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex were suppressed during self-contact, which is also the case when living beings clean themselves. However, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh were amplified during external contact and tickling by the scientists.
However, if the self-contact and the touch by others happen at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed, indicating that the brain of the rat cannot distinguish between the self-contact and the touch by others. However, the new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because the self-contact activates a brake in the cerebrum.
In addition, the rats had been trained to tickle themselves. Therefore, they sometimes interrupted this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showing flight behaviour or fright. This ambivalence is similar to the behaviour of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioural reaction, which is the same in rats and humans.
