Study on causes of heart disease
Smoking, obesity, unhealthy eating - there are risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. But what really triggers heart failure or an infarction? Hamburg researchers now want to take a close look at the genome of 9000 healthy and sick people.
By analysing the genetic make-up of 9000 people, Hamburg and Swiss scientists want to find out more about the causes of cardiovascular diseases.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking world, according to the University Medical Center in Hamburg, Germany. The Kühne Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros. Davos Mountain Clinic, which belongs to the foundation, and Zurich University Hospital are involved from Switzerland.
Obesity, smoking and an unhealthy diet are among the major influenceable risk factors for cardiovascular disease. Genetic factors play a role in determining the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is insufficiently known. Now, the scientists want to compare the complete genetic material of 8,000 healthy people with that of 1,000 former patients of the University Heart and Vascular Centre at the UKE.
Currently, more than 4000 of the approximately 20,000 relevant human genes are known to have potential disease-causing DNA changes - so-called mutations -, according to the clinical centre. Each year, about 200 additional mutations are reported.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, cardiac insufficiency and heart attacks. Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University Heart and Vascular Centre, says that the data could also be used in the research of other common diseases.
The chairman of the Kühne Gesellschaft Foundation, Klaus, Michael Kühne (82), also stressed that there was a firm will to use the data for research into other diseases. So far, the clinic of the foundation in Davos treats mainly allergies. Now, a Center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine is to be established on the local medical campus and a professorship for bioinformatics is to be created. To justify his commitment, the logistics entrepreneur, who lives in Switzerland, said that he had been operated on an open heart in Hamburg three years ago and was very grateful.
The bioprobes of the healthy participants come from Hamburg residents, who are also taking part in the Hamburg City Health Study. With 45,000 test persons, this is the largest local health study in the world, according to the hospital. In the genetic material decoding, strict attention is paid to the protection of anonymised data, the scientists assure. It is about one petabyte (1000 terabyte) of data, said Holger Moch from the University Hospital Zurich.
According to the UKE, the genome of a human being can be deciphered within 24 hours, at a mere material cost of 1300 Euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, the results of which were published in 2001, cost several hundred million Euros. The study is scheduled to begin on 1 October and analyze all 9,000 samples by the end of 2020. Initial results are expected in the following year.
