Comet of other star crosses solar system
Astronomers are currently observing a comet from the depths of space. Previously, this had only been possible once. However, the comet allows conclusions to be drawn about other solar systems.
What was at first only a guess is now confirmed: An interstellar guest crosses through our solar system. The comet from the depth of space was named 2I / Borisov after its discoverer and has aroused the interest of astronomers all over the world.
The widely travelled comet was discovered on 30 August by amateur astronomer Gennady Borisov at the Margo ’ s Observatory in Crimea – with a homemade telescope of 65 centimetres in diameter. Follow-up observations of various observatories not only confirmed that it was an unknown comet, but also showed that it did not originate from our solar system.
After 1I / 'Oumuamua of 2017, 2I / Borisov is only the second interstellar object to be sighted during a flight through our solar system.
2I / Borisov offers astronomers a rare chance to get a close-up view of a foreign solar system before it disappears for good. Initial observations show that the interstellar comet is similar to those of our own system, as reported by the Astrophysical Institute of the Canaries. "The current speed of the comet is high, about 150,000 kilometres per hour, which is much higher at this distance than the typical velocities of objects orbiting the Sun," reported Davide Farnocchia of the US space agency Nasa in a statement.
According to the analyses, the comet travels on a so-called hyperbola orbit, which leads it out of our system - and clearly of interstellar origin, as the International Astronomical Union (IAU) announced. It is also responsible for the naming and categorization of celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, the interstellar comet, which was initially led under the catalog number C / 2019 Q4, was given the designation 2I / Borisov, whereby the first part of the name indicates that it is the second interstellar object that has been discovered in our solar system.
The astronomers are lucky: In contrast to 1I / 'Oumuamua, 2I / Borisov has already been sighted during the approach, leaving many months for the researchers to investigate. "The object will reach the highest brightness in mid-December and will then be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020," explained Farnocchia. "After that, it will only be observable with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020."
Several observatories have already targeted the visitor, with a team led by Karen Meech of the University of Hawaii, who had already led the characterisation of 1I / 'Oumuamua, determining the diameter of the celestial object over 2 to 16 kilometres in an initial study. Images from the Gemini Observatory on Hawaii show a distinct tail of the comet.
Researchers at the Institute of Astrophysics of the Canary Islands (IAC) have already obtained a first so-called spectrum from the interstellar comet, which offers a kind of fingerprint of its chemical composition. "The spectrum of this object is similar to that of comets in our solar system, and this indicates that its composition must be similar," reported IAC, researcher Julia de León. This observation suggests that comets in other solar systems could form through similar processes as in ours, added de León's colleague Javier Licandro.
The IAU estimates that the discovery of two interstellar visitors within only two years suggests that these objects could open up a new way of studying certain processes in other solar systems. However, it is still difficult to estimate how frequent such visits are. One of the next interstellar visitors could possibly be intercepted by a planned satellite mission of the European Space Agency Esa.
By 2028, the agency plans to station the three-part spacecraft "Comet Interceptor" on a waiting position at a distance of 1.5 million kilometres from Earth. According to ESA Science Director Günther Hasinger, the spacecraft is to be lurking either on a still untouched, fresh comet from our own solar system, or on an interstellar visitor such as 1I / 'Oumuamua.
