Half of European tree species threatened with extinction
Apart from pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are also the reasons for the threat, reported the World Conservation Union (IUCN) on Friday in Brussels. It examined the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of these species are not found on any other continent. Of these, 58 per cent are at risk. 66 are already at the highest level of endangerment and are therefore on the verge of extinction.
The IUCN classifies endangered species into six categories: from "potentially endangered" to "endangered", "highly endangered", "threatened with extinction" and "extinct in nature" to "extinct". In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide as endangered.
Rowan and wild horse chestnut threatened
In Germany, rowan trees (Sorbus) are the most endangered species, said one of the authors, David Allen, of the German Press Agency. "Most of them are endangered because the populations are small anyway or by the transformation or weakening of their habitats."
It also looks bad for the wild Common Horse Chestnuts. They have been considered "endangered" since 2017, level two of the IUCN scale. The Balkan miner moths pose the greatest threat in addition to a fungus. They have been spreading from south-eastern Europe over the entire continent since the 1980s and have hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnuts (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe at less than 10,000 specimens. Not included in this assessment are the trees in cities, parks and avenues.
Shrub species and mosses also at risk
At the same time, IUCN scientists established new European red lists for molluscs, shrubs and mosses. According to the IUCN, more than a fifth of molluscs and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened. This is mainly due to the destruction of the wilderness, introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Molluscs and snails play a key role in the recycling of nutrients in the soil and are an important source of food for birds and other animals.
"This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of the European ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet," said Luc Bas, IUCN ’ s Director of the European Office. "We need to limit the impact of humans on our ecosystems and make the protection of these species a priority."
