They are portraits, still lifes, landscapes, several hamsters, a sheep in the kitchen and other interiors from the early seventies to the late nineties. "She wanted real moments," writes the art critic Ekow Eshun in his foreword. And of course one is always at the center: her husband Paul - as you may never have seen him before.
He ’ s dancing with his daughter Mary on his shoulders, telephoning in a bathrobe with a bag on his head, or wearing shapeless Moon Boots. Sure, the McCartneys were an extraordinary family, but beyond the spotlight, they lived a normal life on their farms in the South of England or Scotland. According to the BBC, Mary McCartney said that she slept as a baby in a bed that her father made from old potato boxes, and it wasn ’ t always tidy with the McCartneys.
