Rental suddenly stopped: WeWork makes real estate markets tremble
In New York, WeWork has become the largest office tenant.
Within a few years, WeWork has grown from a small startup to a driving force on the world ’ s most expensive real estate markets. However, the company is now in a crisis. Landlords have to fear for billions in income.
The crisis of the office tenant WeWork threatens to upset the balance in the world ’ s largest real estate markets. A few days ago, the company sold founder Adam Neumann as CEO, postponed the planned IPO and started selling subsidiaries and assets such as the private jet for the executives in order to gain financial leeway for the coming weeks and months. Furthermore, the British Financial Times reports, among others, that WeWork has stopped the completion of new leases with immediate effect. Thus, among others, the largest tenant of office space is suddenly off the market in New York and London.
WeWork rents large office space on a long-term basis and rents it out to members at short notice, sometimes in small units. This can be individual freelancers, small startups or entire departments of large corporations. So far, WeWork has been burning money with this business at breathtaking speed. Last year, the company made a loss of 1.6 billion dollars, with a turnover of 1.8 billion dollars. This year, the rental costs alone are said to have risen to an estimated 2.5 billion dollars due to the lease of more and more large spaces. In order to limit the loss, the new management is now said to have pulled the emergency brake and stopped renting new spaces with immediate effect.
According to the Financial Times, WeWork has now signed leases with terms of up to 15 years, resulting in commitments of more than 40 billion dollars. These huge liabilities could become a problem not only for the company itself and its investors, but also for entire real estate markets.
According to calculations by the economist Dan Alpert from Cornell Law School in New York, WeWork in Manhattan, one of the most expensive real estate markets in the world, has rented almost 300,000 square meters of office space in the past 24 months. WeWork ’ s new contracts alone ensured that the demand for offices in New York was greater than the space newly launched during this period. Without WeWork ’ s expansion, the office in the U.S. metropolis would have increased vacancy during this period, as Alpert wrote in the Business Insider. A similar situation exists in London, where WeWork now operates several dozen office locations in prime locations.
Even in the British capital, the balance in the real estate market could change noticeably without further expansion of the aggressive start-up. WeWork is the main tenant, in an office building in the centre of the financial metropolis that was bought last year by the savings bank Deka for almost 100 million euros.
Many landlords have converted their properties for the requirements of WeWork with high investments. If WeWork fails to make its business model profitable soon, the property owners would probably have to write off a portion of the expected billions of income. They do not have access to the - already scarce - reserves of WeWork despite the long-term leases. Because the leasing of the individual locations of WeWork is usually carried out by specially founded subsidiaries, so-called Special Purpose Vehicles, for which the parent company is only liable within narrow limits.
Russia once again arrested many North Korean fishermen
The Russian Coast Guard has once again taken action against North Korean fishermen. According to the Interfax agency, a total of 262 poachers have been arrested in the past few days who had fished illegally in the waters, according to the Russian Domestic Intelligence Service (FSB) on Friday.
Just ten days ago, 161 fishermen were arrested from North Korea. Previously, the border guards had been shot at and three of them injured, but this time there were no casualties, it was said. Communist North Korea suffers from chronic food shortages.
According to the report, the North Korean fishermen were on their way to Russian territorial waters, where the Russian Coast Guard says it is patrolling to protect its marine biological resources, and that 30,000 octopuses were discovered during the re-inspections, and that three fishing boats and two motor boats were confiscated and taken to Nakhodka and Posjet near Vladivostok. According to the Ria Novosti agency, the Coast Guard found a total of more than 8,000 violations in 2018.
The Russian fisheries authority did not issue fishing licenses to North Koreans this year, according to complaints from domestic entrepreneurs, with thousands of North Korean fishermen having been arrested there temporarily in 2019, according to the media.
The head of the Association of Russian Fisheries Georgi Martynov, a company in the Primorye region of the Far East, recently complained about the high environmental damage caused by North Korean fishermen who fished with close-meshed synthetic nets prohibited in Russia. These nets would also be used to remove small creatures from the sea. Moreover, the nets would simply be disposed of in the sea, where they would take 200 years to decompose, and the ships themselves would not comply with hygienic and technical regulations.
Three members of the Russian Coast Guard were injured during the arrests last week, according to Moscow. According to the FSB, another wounded North Korean died later from his injuries. On 17 September, Russian border guards first detained a North Korean boat and then a second one after it opened fire.
