If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various check options.
Anyone who concludes an Internet contract does not need to trust blindly the speed data of the providers. Customers can check for any anomalies how much is actually achieved.
After all, the previously promised transfer rates are an integral part of the contract and should therefore also be achieved, explains the Consumer Association of Bavaria.
If the connection always seems to be much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options. The measuring tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
"The tests of the offerers take place however after offerer-specific defaults and are therefore not uniformly and objectively computed", gives the consumer center Bavaria on their side to consider.
If the connection is considerably slower than announced, customers can set the provider a reasonable period of time, usually 14 days, to produce the promised service. Concerned parties do this best in writing by registered letter.
If this has no effect even after repeated requests, customers can terminate the contract and claim damages under certain circumstances.
