Aegean: Baby and four other children drown in boat accident
A baby and four other children drowned while a refugee boat capsized in the Aegean Sea. Seven people died in the accident, according to the Greek Coast Guard on Friday. According to the report, the nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men could be saved.
At present, hundreds of migrants from Turkey are crossing over to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean Sea. According to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), 174 people were killed on this route last year. Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced his intention to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU Commissioner, Seehofer said he wanted to be informed in Turkey about "how things stand with regard to the refugee situation" on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the "administrative problems of the Greeks" in Athens in order to be able to help in coping with them.
A spokeswoman for the EU Commission confirmed on Friday the planned trip of Seehofer with the EU Commissioner for Home Affairs Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
An unusually high number of migrants from Turkey continue to arrive in Greece. On Tuesday alone, 654 people transferred to the Greek islands, according to the Greek Ministry for the Protection of Citizens on Wednesday.
Does Turkey ’ s Deal Still Work?
The increased numbers have recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU ’ s 2016 agreement with Turkey, which allows the EU to repatriate all refugees and migrants who arrive illegally to the Greek islands via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to accept a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every Syrian deported.
On the Greek side, however, the processing of asylum applications is only progressing slowly due to a lack of staff. According to the Ministry for Civil Protection, almost 29,400 people are waiting on Lesvos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos. The worst situation is on Lesvos: At present, 5,200 migrants are accommodated in a camp with capacity for 650 people.
Never before have there been so many refugees since the entry into force of the EU / Turkey Refugee Pact in March 2016, reported the state radio.
Climate change: Heat leads to more heart attacks
According to physicians, climate change will put the health system to the test in the future. Climate changes are "quite certain" one of the biggest challenges for the health system in the next 20 to 50 years, said Andreas Zeiher, President of the German Society of Cardiology. Especially the cardiovascular system caused high temperatures and large temperature jumps within a short time and led increasingly to heart attacks. Especially people with cardiovascular diseases, elderly people and diabetics are affected.
Green politician has to answer for embarrassing photo breakdown
The leader of the Canadian Green Party, Elizabeth May, during the election campaign - was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green Party boss holds in a photo a multi-way cup in his hand. But now came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa / Canada - It went unnoticed for quite a while - and finally caught the eye. Elizabeth May, the leader of the Canadian Green Party, never held the reusable coffee mug with metal straw in her hand. On the party's website, she was seen on a photo with this mug, talking to citizens. However, the photo had already been published and also distributed to the media - and the mug was still a despicable (cardboard) mug, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Green Party leader has to answer for photo breakdown
The National Post then accused May of manipulation, and accused the party of producing fake news in order to gain credibility on the issue of environmental protection, in the midst of a campaign for the House of Commons, in which Trudeau, too, is increasingly struggling because of a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media and sparked discussion about fake news. A user shares a juxtaposition of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their chairman to conceal their disposable cup."
May was shocked and claimed on her blog not to have known about this action. To underline this, she immediately posted the original: She, talking to citizens, a cup in her hand. However, she put it right, is made of bamboo. She always has it with her. A spokeswoman of the party said, it was only about to place the party logo in the picture, and not to cover up something. Of the photo can be seen on the website only a detail.
May writes that she is sorry for the employee who did this. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide," she says to the Guardian and at the same time asks something of her over-engaged team: "If they want to work on an image again, could they not do something with my face so that I look younger?"
Also the German Greens are because of their use of disposable plastic or because of air travel in Shitstorms - their pictures were not fotoshops. So the head of the Bavarian Greens, Katharina Schulze, ate on holiday ice cream with plastic spoon, as reported merkur.de *.
Influencerin wants Free Upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Allegedly Jaqueline Ng was promised an upgrade by mail from Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at the check in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously get an upgrade for Business Class - this is what many passengers dream of. Sometimes they are lucky and the check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class free of charge.
This case shows, however, how not to do it: A self-declared influencer has asked the airline Cathay Pacific actively for a free upgrade. On Instagram follow Jaqueline Ng more than 65.000 Users. On 30. Never it flew back from Taiwan to New York and on 7. June.
On the outward flight, employees refused to upgrade Jaqueline, although she had shown an email in which Cathay Pacific allegedly promised her an upgrade. Influencerin said to have received the letter from a marketing team member of the airline. However, the airline accused Jaqueline of forging the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to obtain an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were sceptical: They checked with the headquarters. And, in fact, the employee, from whom the mail supposedly originated, denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
The airline ’ s employees at the airport cancelled Jaqueline ’ s ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (around 1,280 euros), she had to buy a new flight ticket to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencerin turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests, because although Cathay had reimbursed her for her original ticket, Jaqueline also claimed back the costs of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencerin has committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. Furthermore, the airline's terms and conditions state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with it - and now turns to a lawyer.
Oil prices down following ceasefire report in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than one dollar at midday on Friday. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The price slide was triggered by a Wall Street Journal report on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
In mid-September, a drone attack on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had brought five percent of the world ’ s oil production to a standstill. Meanwhile, the Iranian-allied Houthi rebels in Yemen ’ s civil war country had claimed responsibility for the attacks. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse the political tension in the region.
If an agreement is reached, the focus can be on growth and demand, said Ole Hansen, head of commodity strategy at Saxo Bank, Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices are thus continuing the downward trend of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI still cost up to nearly 59 dollars, Brent nearly 65 dollars.
More recently, Bloomberg, citing insiders, reported that repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than expected following the attack in mid-September. According to the report, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press releases referring to insiders, which report on rapid progress of the state oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco currently plans an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, some easing in the conflict between Iran and Western countries has been indicated: the British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leave the port more than two months after being arrested by Iran and the recently granted clearance. Now, the crew is preparing the departure, while the ship is still at anchor, Shipping Manager Erik Hånell informed Swedish Radio on Friday morning in a text message.
However, the US announced that it would redeploy defensive missiles and soldiers to Iran ’ s arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and the United Kingdom had temporarily pushed up oil prices considerably in recent weeks.
Accusations against Trump intensify
According to an anonymous whistleblower, in the case of the possible abuse of power by US President Donald Trump, allegations of cover-up against the White House have been heard. Several senior officials have made intensive efforts to prevent access to the wording of the conversation after a controversial telephone conversation between Trump and Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky at the end of July. Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi explicitly accused the White House of "cover-up." Trump spoke of a "witch-hunt."
North Korea ’ s Third Trump and Kim Summit in Question
North Korea has raised doubts that a third summit between rulers Kim Jong Il and US President Donald Trump will soon take place in the nuclear dispute, but the purpose and prospects of such a meeting are questionable due to the lack of progress in implementing the first summit agreements in Singapore, said senior diplomat Kim Kye gwan on Friday, according to the agency KCNA.
The US has done nothing to implement the decisions of the summit last year, said the advisor to the North Korean State Department. He also criticised the US sanctions and the joint military manoeuvres of the US and South Korea. However, he hopes for a "wise" and "courageous" decision by Trump, so that a rapprochement can come again.
Trump said on Monday that he wanted to know what a third summit with Kim would bring before he agreed to do so. Negotiations on the disarmament of North Korea ’ s nuclear and missile program have stalled since the failed second Trump / Kim summit in Hanoi in February. Then, in June, the two met in the demilitarized zone between the two Korean states, agreeing to revive the talks, but with little success.
Prince Harry: Weapon manufacturers to help clear mines
Wearing a blue splinter protection vest, British Prince Harry symbolically detonated and destroyed an explosive mine in Angola. Near a camp of the British Halo Trust near the village of Dirico, he manufactured the ignition circuit. At a safe distance, the explosive exploded. In view of the goal of getting Angola mine-free by 2025, he later demanded in front of running TV cameras: "I call on all countries whose names are on these weapons, but which have not helped to clear them away, to commit themselves to help."
Pound under pressure - interest rate cut expected
British pound under pressure
With interest rates falling soon, the pound is falling against the euro.
Frankfurt Speculation of an imminent interest rate cut by the Bank of England (BoE) is hitting the pound sterling, with the British currency sinking by up to 0.4 percent to $1.2269 on Friday.
Sales were triggered by statements by central banker Michael Saunders, who raised the issue of lowering interest rates, even if a chaotic Brexit could be averted, as uncertainty would affect the UK economy in the foreseeable future. Saunders ’ statement was surprising, as he was seen as an advocate of a restrictive monetary policy, said analyst Ricardo Evangelista of Brokerhaus ActivTrades.
Last week, the Bank of England had already pointed out the economic burden of Brexit, without directly signaling an interest rate cut. Prime Minister Boris Johnson wants to lead his country out of the EU on October 31, if necessary, even without a divorce agreement.
More: With his provocations, the British Prime Minister has taken a high risk. However, it could pay off for him, says Handelsblatt, editor Kerstin Leitel.
Doping: Further Russian manipulations proven
This is confirmed by David Howman, former director of the World Antidoping Agency (Wada) and current head of the integrity of the World Federation of Athletics.
At the start of the World Championships in Athletics, new details about the doping scandal in Russia come to light - and they destroy the little credibility that Russian sport had regained at the beginning of the year and even only partially. In January 2019, the Moscow doping laboratory finally delivered the required samples from the years 2012 to 2015 to the World Anti Doping Agency (Wada).
In December 2014, systematic fraud in Russian sports was revealed, after which the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (Rusada) was closed for three years by Wada. During this period, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. After individual testing at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio, the International Olympic Committee allowed around 270 athletes from the country to compete under a neutral flag; 168 Russian athletes took part in the Winter Games in February 2018. They were also allowed to take part in the World Cups in the various sports, and in the summer, Russia even hosted the Football World Cup.
Positive findings missing
The following September, the Wada repealed Rusada ’ s ban, but requested access to the laboratory and to the samples in question, in order to clarify the extent of the cover-up of doping cases in state doping, and to help punish athletes after the event. Finally, three months later, the data were delivered.
The Chairman of the Independent Integrity Commission (AIU) of the World Athletics Federation (IAAF) has now confirmed that doping has been manipulated data from the Moscow Analysis Laboratory. "Yes. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the task force has received the right data," said David Howman in an interview with the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung" on Friday. "We have identified numerous discrepancies between the data that the Wada received from a whistleblower and those that it received from the Russians in January." Many positive findings mentioned in the McLaren's report were missing.
The World Cup not affected
This confirms the IAAF ’ s stance: the Athletics Association is the only organisation to maintain the ban on Russia. Thirty Russian athletes will start at the World Championships in Doha under a neutral flag. They had to prove that they are training outside the Russian system and undergo tests.
At the beginning of this week, the Wada had already brought manipulations into the room and asked Russia to respond to the accusations within three weeks. Russia is now threatening to ban the Rusada again and, in the worst case scenario, to be excluded from the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo.
